{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":359,"text":"This is a thousand-year-old drawing of the brain."},{"time":4355,"text":"It's a diagram of the visual system."},{"time":6267,"text":"And some things look very familiar today."},{"time":9017,"text":"Two eyes at the bottom, optic nerve flowing out from the back."},{"time":13384,"text":"There's a very large nose"},{"time":15504,"text":"that doesn't seem to be connected to anything in particular."}]},{"cues":[{"time":18821,"text":"And if we compare this"},{"time":20521,"text":"to more recent representations of the visual system,"},{"time":22595,"text":"you'll see that things have gotten substantially more complicated"},{"time":25552,"text":"over the intervening thousand years."},{"time":27125,"text":"And that's because today we can see what's inside of the brain,"},{"time":30090,"text":"rather than just looking at its overall shape."}]},{"cues":[{"time":32571,"text":"Imagine you wanted to understand how a computer works"},{"time":36550,"text":"and all you could see was a keyboard, a mouse, a screen."},{"time":39729,"text":"You really would be kind of out of luck."},{"time":42125,"text":"You want to be able to open it up, crack it open,"},{"time":44167,"text":"look at the wiring inside."},{"time":46011,"text":"And up until a little more than a century ago,"},{"time":47875,"text":"nobody was able to do that with the brain."},{"time":49875,"text":"Nobody had had a glimpse of the brain's wiring."}]},{"cues":[{"time":51755,"text":"And that's because if you take a brain out of the skull"},{"time":54707,"text":"and you cut a thin slice of it,"},{"time":56396,"text":"put it under even a very powerful microscope,"},{"time":58894,"text":"there's nothing there."},{"time":60075,"text":"It's gray, formless."},{"time":61688,"text":"There's no structure. It won't tell you anything."}]},{"cues":[{"time":64292,"text":"And this all changed in the late 19th century."},{"time":67146,"text":"Suddenly, new chemical stains for brain tissue were developed"},{"time":71021,"text":"and they gave us our first glimpses at brain wiring."},{"time":73833,"text":"The computer was cracked open."}]},{"cues":[{"time":75846,"text":"So what really launched modern neuroscience"},{"time":78702,"text":"was a stain called the Golgi stain."},{"time":80667,"text":"And it works in a very particular way."},{"time":82548,"text":"Instead of staining all of the cells inside of a tissue,"},{"time":85658,"text":"it somehow only stains about one percent of them."},{"time":88690,"text":"It clears the forest, reveals the trees inside."},{"time":92032,"text":"If everything had been labeled, nothing would have been visible."},{"time":94704,"text":"So somehow it shows what's there."}]},{"cues":[{"time":96750,"text":"Spanish neuroanatomist Santiago Ramon y Cajal,"},{"time":99417,"text":"who's widely considered the father of modern neuroscience,"},{"time":102262,"text":"applied this Golgi stain, which yields data which looks like this,"},{"time":106159,"text":"and really gave us the modern notion of the nerve cell, the neuron."},{"time":109917,"text":"And if you're thinking of the brain as a computer,"},{"time":112531,"text":"this is the transistor."},{"time":114542,"text":"And very quickly Cajal realized"},{"time":116617,"text":"that neurons don't operate alone,"},{"time":118954,"text":"but rather make connections with others"},{"time":120792,"text":"that form circuits just like in a computer."},{"time":123298,"text":"Today, a century later, when researchers want to visualize neurons,"},{"time":126689,"text":"they light them up from the inside rather than darkening them."},{"time":129456,"text":"And there's several ways of doing this."},{"time":130606,"text":"But one of the most popular ones"},{"time":132333,"text":"involves green fluorescent protein."},{"time":134425,"text":"Now green fluorescent protein,"},{"time":136084,"text":"which oddly enough comes from a bioluminescent jellyfish,"},{"time":139229,"text":"is very useful."},{"time":140467,"text":"Because if you can get the gene for green fluorescent protein"},{"time":143105,"text":"and deliver it to a cell,"},{"time":144780,"text":"that cell will glow green --"},{"time":146527,"text":"or any of the many variants now of green fluorescent protein,"},{"time":150273,"text":"you get a cell to glow many different colors."}]},{"cues":[{"time":151937,"text":"And so coming back to the brain,"},{"time":153458,"text":"this is from a genetically engineered mouse called \"Brainbow.\""},{"time":157258,"text":"And it's so called, of course,"},{"time":158808,"text":"because all of these neurons are glowing different colors."}]},{"cues":[{"time":162420,"text":"Now sometimes neuroscientists need to identify"},{"time":165871,"text":"individual molecular components of neurons, molecules,"},{"time":168915,"text":"rather than the entire cell."},{"time":170713,"text":"And there's several ways of doing this,"},{"time":172419,"text":"but one of the most popular ones"},{"time":173888,"text":"involves using antibodies."},{"time":176083,"text":"And you're familiar, of course,"},{"time":177420,"text":"with antibodies as the henchmen of the immune system."},{"time":180371,"text":"But it turns out that they're so useful to the immune system"},{"time":182789,"text":"because they can recognize specific molecules,"},{"time":185339,"text":"like, for example, the coat protein"},{"time":187458,"text":"of a virus that's invading the body."},{"time":189846,"text":"And researchers have used this fact"},{"time":191891,"text":"in order to recognize specific molecules inside of the brain,"},{"time":196216,"text":"recognize specific substructures of the cell"},{"time":198856,"text":"and identify them individually."}]},{"cues":[{"time":201100,"text":"And a lot of the images I've been showing you here are very beautiful,"},{"time":204125,"text":"but they're also very powerful."},{"time":206031,"text":"They have great explanatory power."},{"time":207667,"text":"This, for example, is an antibody staining"},{"time":209757,"text":"against serotonin transporters in a slice of mouse brain."}]},{"cues":[{"time":213277,"text":"And you've heard of serotonin, of course,"},{"time":214958,"text":"in the context of diseases like depression and anxiety."},{"time":217785,"text":"You've heard of SSRIs,"},{"time":219193,"text":"which are drugs that are used to treat these diseases."},{"time":222090,"text":"And in order to understand how serotonin works,"},{"time":224980,"text":"it's critical to understand where the serontonin machinery is."},{"time":228056,"text":"And antibody stainings like this one"},{"time":229652,"text":"can be used to understand that sort of question."}]},{"cues":[{"time":233198,"text":"I'd like to leave you with the following thought:"},{"time":235756,"text":"Green fluorescent protein and antibodies"},{"time":238366,"text":"are both totally natural products at the get-go."},{"time":241373,"text":"They were evolved by nature"},{"time":244152,"text":"in order to get a jellyfish to glow green for whatever reason,"},{"time":246719,"text":"or in order to detect the coat protein of an invading virus, for example."},{"time":251102,"text":"And only much later did scientists come onto the scene"},{"time":254119,"text":"and say, \"Hey, these are tools,"},{"time":256142,"text":"these are functions that we could use"},{"time":258255,"text":"in our own research tool palette.\""},{"time":260263,"text":"And instead of applying feeble human minds"},{"time":263891,"text":"to designing these tools from scratch,"},{"time":265775,"text":"there were these ready-made solutions right out there in nature"},{"time":268679,"text":"developed and refined steadily for millions of years"},{"time":271915,"text":"by the greatest engineer of all."},{"time":273615,"text":"Thank you."},{"time":274877,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}